A lot of Northwest African history is oral. What we know of our ancient heritage was told by foreigners—Egyptians, Greeks, Romans. This project, amongst many by Maghrebi creatives, strives to change that by taking charge of our own stories, our own history.
These paintings are part of the artist’s Identity project, seeking to create national unity by redefining what it means to Libyan, and by extension, what it means to be North African.

The Flute of Libya

This one depicts the personification of the Greek city & archeological site, Cyrene, playing one of the oldest flutes—the aulos or kalamos—made of the Libyan lotus plant. Alongside walks the lion she, according to myth, wrestled away from her father’s flock. https://t.co/fKxKZJpu3j

Funeral rituals in the Acacus

A reimagining of the mural discovered by the archaeologist, Fabrizio Mori, in the Acacus Mountains, it depicts the regional funerary rituals & the use of solar boats in them. https://t.co/2ExbvugQ6y

Sahara Chariots — The Garamantes

The painting, inspired by the desert drawings depicting horses & chariots, portrays the Garamantes, in the period between 2700-1500 BC. These chariots linked the city of Gramma, in the heart of the desert, with the coast and created a trade road. https://t.co/4UkiyNSJZV

Silphium Goddess 2.0:

The plant was widely renowned & valued in ancient times as a food source, a seasoning, and, most importantly, as a medicinal panacea, which could cure a variety of ills. https://t.co/0clUdd2lzu

The Silphium Goddess

Inspired by Greek-Libyan coins, this painting depicts Silphium—or Silphion—an extinct plant the Greeks believed was a gift from the healing god Apollo who, according to tradition, carried the nymph Kyrene to Africa & founded the city bearing her name. https://t.co/HYCCISqLen

The Night of the Nine Blows

This painting portrays Meryey, the king of the Libu tribe, and Keber, the king of the Meshwesh tribe, who assembled an alliance with the Sea Peoples to go to war against the pharaoh Merneptah in the 13th century BC. https://t.co/KPIIzSaAlq

Disclaimer: These are all description I summarised. For more information, you can visit the artist’s official website here.

I can name numerous cases where this has happened, particularly in YA SFF.  And I would advise authors—all authors—to simply not use marginalised cultures they have not lived within or communities they’ve never engaged extensively with in their day to day life. 3/3

I’ve been thinking about this a lot after a conversation my Maghrebi friends and I had on accents and languages and classism.

I wish we’d leave behind the internalised racism and prejudices and focus on celebrating our various colourful accents.

Also, accents give character. They carry pieces of your mother tongue. They epitomise who you are and make everyone so much more interesting.

If you have a strong foreign accent speaking in English or any other language, cherish it.

There’s no such thing as a “perfect accent.”

As long as you’re understandable and can communicate your point, you’re perfectly fluent in the language.

Very tired of the classist, xenophobic, and racist takes people (especially Anglo and Francophones) have on foreign accents.

Those who died on Italian soil never saw home again, and my heart aches for their troubled spirits. On this day, I remember them, Omar Al-Mukhtar, and all those who were forced to give their lives, under an occupation of terror, so that their people might see freedom again.
The deportees were subjected to various tests and experiments set out to study the differences between the colonised and Italian criminals. As you can imagine, they were extremely racist.

Hundreds of Libyans, deemed “insane,” were taken to the hospitals at Aversa (Caserta, Campania). This was a period where an interest in Psychiatry was growing, and the presence of the colonised caught the intrigue of anthropologists, criminologists, and physicians.

The deportees were often met by angry mobs. At the penal colonies, their labour was exploited, despite concerns from local authorities, and large fractions of each group died from the unsanitary conditions, frigid temperatures, and the unsuitable barracks they were stationed at.

Disease spread like wildfire on the ship, many died along the way—this is the main reason why estimates vary—and those who did survive the journey, were plagued with a terrible bout of Cholera, rendering them weak and sickly.

During the First World War, the deportees were sent first to Syracuse, then they were separated: male adults were sent to Favignana, children and minors to Noto (Syracuse), and women to the female penitentiary in Trani (Bari, Puglia region).

Coerced deportations lasted throughout the entire colonial period, 1911-1943, and though estimates vary, thousands are believed to have been deported, the majority before WWI. Deportations dwindled under the Facists due to the use of concentration camps within the colony.

This photograph was taken after the first deportation to Ustica was completed. The prisoners in their traditional white robes fade into the background, ghosts destined to disappear, while the five guards in the foreground are pencilled in. 

The contrast is haunting to look at. https://t.co/2K0a1ytYhB

Libyans were deported en massse (including civilians, women, minors, and elderly) to either one of the various penal colonies—the islands of Ustica, Tremiti, Favigana, Ponza, and the military penitentiary Goeta—or Sicily, specifically Palermo. 

Most, if not all, never returned.

Before Mussolini and the Fascist regime came into power, after the revolt on Shara Al-Shatt, the Italian authorities sought a method to weaken the resistance without continuing the massacres of Libyans by Italian soldiers—the sign of a military’s weakness.

On this day 90 years ago, Omar Al-Mukhtar was executed by Italian colonial forces for resisting the occupation. We commemorate the sacrifices made by all of our fallen heroes. And today, I want to talk to you about some Libyan martyrs you may not have heard of: 

The Deportees. https://t.co/akDkmpjcde
